DTSTAMP:20260706T023641Z
DTSTART:20260716T183000Z
DTEND:20260716T203000Z
SUMMARY:Powering the PNW: Fission\, Fusion\, and the Future of Firm Clean E
 nergy
LOCATION:2333 Seaway Blvd\, Everett\, WA
DESCRIPTION:Source: Luma\n\nWashington State is sprinting toward a 100% cle
 an grid by 2045\, but the explosive energy demands of AI data centers and 
 rapid electrification are straining our existing hydropower foundation.\n\
 nJoin us during PNW Climate Week to explore how next-generation nuclear te
 chnologies can deliver the clean\, firm baseload power the region desperat
 ely needs.\n\n🗓️ What to Expect\n\nThe AI Baseload Imperative: Why wi
 nd\, solar\, and batteries need a firm-power partner to keep the grid stab
 le.\n\nScaling SMRs: The real-world timelines and economics of bringing Sm
 all Modular Reactors to Washington State.\n\nPolicy & Public Trust: Stream
 lining the siting process\, aligning with state mandates\, and prioritizin
 g environmental justice.\n\n🎤 The Panel\n\nZabrina Johal\, CEO\, Zap En
 ergy (confirmed)\nLeading the Everett-based startup's bold new dual-track 
 strategy to commercialize both advanced fission microreactors and fusion t
 echnology.\n\nAndrew Eckert\, Director of Commercial Strategy\, TerraPower
  (confirmed)\nDeveloping advanced\, molten salt reactor to bring carbon-fr
 ee energy to the grid while generating isotopes for precision medicine.\n\
 nJackie Eustey\, Strategic Outreach Program Manager - New Nuclear Developm
 ent\, Energy Northwest (confirmed)\nSpearheading regional initiatives to d
 eploy advanced SMRs and operating the Northwest’s only commercial nuclea
 r plant.\n\nAmí Hafkemeyer\, Director of Siting and Compliance\, Washingt
 on State Energy Facility Site Evaluation Council (confirmed) \nProviding t
 he regulatory perspective on how state energy siting processes and timelin
 es will affect advanced nuclear projects in the region.\n\n🕒 Agenda\n\n
 11:30 AM: Doors Open & Networking\n\n11:40 AM: Introductions\, Presentatio
 n & Panel Discussion\n\n12:30 PM: Audience Q&A\n\n12:45 PM: Networking\n\n
 1:30 PM: Event Wraps\n\nLocation: SNBL Global Gateway\, 2333 Seaway Blvd\,
  Everett\, WA 98203\nWho Should Attend: Energy professionals\, climate tec
 h founders\, policymakers\, and grid enthusiasts.\n\nBy registering for th
 is event\, you agree to share your information with the event organizers\,
  PNW Climate Week\, and Climatebase / the Climate Week Network. You may re
 ceive updates from these organizations\, and can opt out at any time in ac
 cordance with their respective privacy policies\n\nCalendar: Plug and Play
  Seattle\n\nHosts: Plug and Play Seattle\, CleanTech Alliance\, PNW Climat
 e Week\, Momo Nakamura\, Ben Eisinger\n\nVenue: 2333 Seaway Blvd\n\nEvent 
 page: https://luma.com/qxg1f8r9
URL:https://luma.com/qxg1f8r9
STATUS:CONFIRMED
TRANSP:OPAQUE
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:evt-eqivftv2lDaVDCU@luma.com
DTSTAMP:20260706T023641Z
DTSTART:20260716T193000Z
DTEND:20260716T204500Z
SUMMARY:State of Climate Tech VC in the PNW 2026 Round Table - Live Podcast
  Recording
LOCATION:Founders Hall (FNDR)\, Seattle\, WA
DESCRIPTION:Source: Luma\n\nWhere is climate capital actually flowing in 20
 26 — and where has it stalled?\n\nFive investors working across the clim
 ate tech landscape sit down for an unscripted roundtable on the state of t
 he market: what's getting funded\, who's financing first-of-a-kind deploym
 ent\, whether AI and climate are genuinely converging\, and how the Pacifi
 c Northwest stacks up as an ecosystem.\n\nThis is a conversation\, not a p
 anel of prepared remarks. Each investor brings a question they're wrestlin
 g with and puts it to the group.\n\nFeaturing:\n\nSusan Su — Toba Capita
 l\; co-host\, Climate Money podcast\n\nBen Eidelson — Stepchange Venture
 s\; host\, The Stepchange Show\n\nJonathan Azoff — SNØCAP Venture Capit
